answers.body_markdown:
First, let me answer the question directly.  This is logically what IAM is doing.


 1. Evaluate all the identity policy statements.
 2. Do any Deny policy statements evaluate too True.  If so deny the request.
 3. Do any of the Allow policy statements evaluate too True.  If so accept the request
 4. Deny the request because there is no allow statement that evaluated too true.

For use case 1 above:

 1. If tag &quot;allow&quot; is set the user is allowed. This is because 1 or both of the statements will always be true.
 2. If the tag &quot;allow&quot; is not set then the user is denied.  This is because neither statement will be true. 

To only allow the user access if tag &quot;allow&quot; is set to true you need the following:
```
{
    &quot;Version&quot;: &quot;2012-10-17&quot;,
    &quot;Statement&quot;: [
        {
            &quot;Effect&quot;: &quot;Allow&quot;,
            &quot;Action&quot;: &quot;secretsmanager:*&quot;,
            &quot;Resource&quot;: &quot;*&quot;,
            &quot;Condition&quot;: {
                &quot;StringEquals&quot;: {
                    &quot;secretsmanager:ResourceTag/allow&quot;: &quot;True&quot;
                }
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

Use case #2 above:

The user will always be granted access because of the first policy statement is always true.

Now what if only want to allow access if and only if the tag &quot;allow&quot; is set too true.  You need to explicitly deny when it is not true.:
```
{
    &quot;Version&quot;: &quot;2012-10-17&quot;,
    &quot;Statement&quot;: [
        {
            &quot;Effect&quot;: &quot;Allow&quot;,
            &quot;Action&quot;: &quot;secretsmanager:*&quot;,
            &quot;Resource&quot;: &quot;*&quot;,
            &quot;Condition&quot;: {
                &quot;StringEquals&quot;: {
                    &quot;secretsmanager:ResourceTag/allow&quot;: &quot;True&quot;
                }
            }
        },
        {
            &quot;Effect&quot;: &quot;Deny&quot;,
            &quot;Action&quot;: &quot;secretsmanager:*&quot;,
            &quot;Resource&quot;: &quot;*&quot;,
            &quot;Condition&quot;: {
                &quot;StringNotEquals&quot;: {
                    &quot;secretsmanager:ResourceTag/allow&quot;: &quot;True&quot;
                }
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

This time we ad an explicit deny policy to guarantee that the &quot;allow&quot; tag is set. 


Now for a little more information in the wonders of IAM.

There are 11 decision points in [AWS IAM Policy Evaluation Logic][1].  6 paths to deny and only 2 to allow.  But this graph should help you figure it.

[![enter image description here][2]][2]

In the case of [multiple statements in the condition][3] multiple statements are &quot;boolean and&quot; and multi values are &quot;boolean or&quot;.

[![enter image description here][4]][4]


  [1]: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/reference_policies_evaluation-logic.html
  [2]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/RcRzv.png
  [3]: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/reference_policies_multi-value-conditions.html
  [4]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/7p1XG.png

